            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Scott Miller\u2019s life didn\u2019t find its direction in a flash of youthful inspiration, but rather through the quiet, steady observation of compassion. Raised in a working-class Cleveland neighborhood, the son of a steelworker and a receptionist, Scott\u2019s future was expected to be practical and local. After high school, he drifted through his twenties, playing bass in a modestly successful local band and working a series of unfulfilling service jobs. The catalyst for change arrived in the form of his mother\u2019s cancer diagnosis. During her prolonged illness, Scott was profoundly moved by the skill, empathy, and quiet dignity of her hospice nurses. They weren't just administering medicine; they were managing pain, counseling the family, and providing a sense of order amidst chaos. This was a purpose he could understand.\n\nAt 29, he enrolled in a community college nursing program, earning his Associate\u2019s degree and RN license. After his mother passed, the ties to Cleveland felt severed. Seeking a new start, he followed a friend to San Francisco, drawn by the city\u2019s promise of acceptance and opportunity. He initially took a grueling job on a med-surg floor at a large hospital but found the relentless pace draining his empathy. The turning point came when he saw a posting for a school nurse at a large public high school. The role was a perfect fit, combining his clinical skills with the social assistance aspect that first drew him to the profession.\n\nToday, Scott\u2019s life is one of structured stability. He lives in a small, cozy home in the Outer Sunset with his partner of twelve years, David, a graphic designer, and their scruffy terrier mix, Gus. His daily 9.5-mile commute on the N-Judah MUNI line is a cherished ritual, a time for reading and mentally preparing for a day of patching scraped knees, addressing anxiety, and being a consistent, calming presence for hundreds of teenagers. He loves the foggy, quiet anonymity of his neighborhood, a peaceful retreat from the city's core. His aspirations are not grand; he dreams of retiring comfortably with David, traveling to Southeast Asia, and perhaps mentoring a new generation of school nurses. For Scott, success isn't defined by wealth or status, but by the quiet satisfaction of a life built on purpose and care."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1. He remembers the low, constant hum of the oxygen concentrator in his childhood living room. His mother was asleep, and her hospice nurse, a woman named Brenda, was gently sponging her forehead. She spoke to his mom in a soft murmur, as if sharing a secret. In that moment, watching the nurse\u2019s practiced, compassionate hands, Scott didn\u2019t just see a job. He saw an act of profound grace in the face of chaos, and for the first time in his aimless life, he felt the pull of a true purpose. This was in Cleveland, a year before he\u2019d lose her.\n\n2. Scott met David not at a bar, but under the fluorescent lights of an SPCA adoption event in the Mission. David was coaxing a terrified, scruffy terrier mix from the back of a crate with a piece of jerky. Scott knelt beside him, and they bonded over the dog's shivering anxiety. David\u2019s laugh was the easiest thing Scott had ever heard. Driving home that day with the newly-named Gus in a box on David\u2019s lap, Scott felt a sense of belonging he hadn\u2019t realized he was so desperately missing. This was twelve years ago.\n\n3. His first commute after quitting the hospital job remains crystal clear. Instead of bracing for the shrill beeps of the med-surg floor, he sat on the N-Judah as it rumbled toward the ocean, a worn paperback in his lap. The train surfaced at Duboce Park, sunlight flooding the car. He looked at the other placid, morning commuters and felt himself exhale a breath he hadn't realized he'd been holding for two years. That morning, the 9.5-mile journey became a ritual of decompression and hope, a transition into a life he was actively choosing.\n\n4. About a month into his job as a school nurse, a lanky freshman came into his office, claiming a headache but unable to make eye contact. Scott recognized the vibrating energy of anxiety immediately. He didn't ask questions. He just handed the boy a cold glass of water and said the office was a quiet place to sit for a few minutes. After five silent minutes, the boy simply whispered, \u201cThanks,\u201d and left. Scott knew then he\u2019d found the right place. He wasn't just fixing bodies; he was creating a tiny pocket of safety.\n\n5. Their first morning in the Outer Sunset house, Scott woke to see the fog had completely swallowed the street, creating a soft, gray cocoon around them. David was already making coffee, the smell mixing with the salty air. Gus was asleep at the foot of the bed. There was no grand revelation, just a quiet, unshakable feeling of rightness. This small house, this man, this dog, this peaceful neighborhood\u2014this was the life he had built, piece by piece. It was more than he had ever thought to ask for."
